name: N,N'-diphenylbenzidine

In the case of N,N'-diphenylbenzidine, the basic unit we can consider is biphenyl, which has a melting point of around 70°C. Next, we need to account for the influence of the amino groups and the connecting carbon chain. Amino groups typically increase the melting point due to the potential for hydrogen bonding and increased polarity, which enhances intermolecular forces. Each phenyl group adds more π-π interactions and van der Waals forces, which can also raise the melting point. The symmetrical structure of N,N'-diphenylbenzidine promotes efficient packing in the solid state, which further increases the melting point. Given that we have two amino groups and a total of four phenyl rings added to the biphenyl structure, we can predict an additive effect on the melting point.
